Based on my work, I would argue that bells are used as both harder and softer ways of provoking responsibility

@dublincycling @PatKennyNT @CiaranCuffe Based on my PhD research, bell ringing can be used in different patterned ways by cyclists in Dublin as a means of provoking responsibility in other roads users to respect their entitlement to public space under conditions of precarious entitlement where disregard is routine

@dublincycling @CiaranCuffe @PatKennyNT Clear indications of formal entitlement I am definitely in favor of - I like large bicycle symbols in bus lanes for example because equal entitlement is clear. Yeah I think 'pedestrian priority' is a creative way to resolve conflicts in shared space.

@CiaranCuffe @dublincycling @PatKennyNT Fascinating Ciaran, so that's a shared space then I assume? It's interesting in DCU they have signs up with 'pedestrian priority' so cycling is allowed but provided there is deference to pedestrians who are given superior entitlement.

@Photaculous @dublincycling @CiaranCuffe @PatKennyNT Thanks for sharing this Tom, I have never actually seen this sign before nor was I aware of a code of conduct in areas of Ireland. Nice to see that the pedestrian priority concept is being used.

@dublincycling @PatKennyNT @CiaranCuffe The context is key though, asserting entitlement and accentuating presence both take place within conditions where disregard of cyclists and cyclist space is routine and there is a perceived lack of police support and secure space
